han Wild, and Jack Sheppard Captivated London and Created the Celebrity Criminal\" by Aaron Skirboll\n"}
{"id": "8194", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=8194", "title": "December 8", "text": "December 8\n\nBULLET::::- 395 – Later Yan is defeated by its former vassal Northern Wei at the Battle of Canhe Slope.\nBULLET::::- 757 – Du Fu returns to Chang'an as a member of Emperor Xuanzong's court, after having escaped the city during the An Lushan Rebellion.\nBULLET::::- 877 – Louis the Stammerer (son of Charles the Bald) is crowned king of the West Frankish Kingdom at Compiègne.\nBULLET::::- 1432 – The first battle between the forces of Švitrigaila and Sigismund Kęstutaitis is fought near the town of Oszmiana (Ashmyany), launching the most active phase of the Lithuanian Civil War.\nBULLET::::- 1504 – Ahmad ibn Abi Jum'ah penned his Oran fatwa, arguing for the relaxation of Islamic law requirements for the forcibly converted Muslims in Spain.\nBULLET::::- 1660 – A woman (either Margaret Hughes or Anne Marshall) appears on an English public stage for the first time, in the role of Desdemona in a production of Shakespeare's play \"Othello\".\nBULLET::::- 1813 – Premiere of Beethoven's Seventh Symphony.\nBULLET::::- 1854 – In his Apostolic constitution \"Ineffabilis Deus\", Pope Pius IX proclaims the dogmatic definition of Immaculate Conception, which holds that the Blessed Virgin Mary was conceived free of Original Sin.\nBULLET::::- 1864 – Pope Pius IX promulgates the encyclical \"Quanta cura\" and its appendix, the \"Syllabus of Errors\", outlining the authority of the Catholic Church and condemning various liberal ideas.\nBULLET::::- 1907 – King Gustaf V of Sweden accedes to the Swedish throne.\nBULLET::::- 1912 – Leaders of the German Empire hold an Imperial War Council to discuss the possibility that war might break out.\nBULLET::::- 1914 – World War I: A squadron of Britain's Royal Navy defeats the Imperial German East Asia Squadron in the Battle of the Falkland Islands in the South Atlantic.\nBULLET::::- 1922 – Northern Ireland ceases to be part of the Irish Free State.\nBULLET::::- 1927 – The Brookings Institution, one of the United States' oldest think tanks, is founded through the merger of three organizations that had been created by philanthropist Robert S. Brookings.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: U.S. President Franklin D. Roosevelt declares December 7 to be \"a date which will live in infamy\", after which the U.S. declares war on Japan.\nBULLET::::- 1941 – World War II: Japanese forces simultaneously invade Shanghai International Settlement, Malaya, Thailand, Hong Kong, the Philippines, and the Dutch East Indies. (See December 7 for the concurrent attack on Pearl Harbor in the Western Hemisphere.)\nBULLET::::- 1943 – World War II: The German 117th Jäger Division destroys the monastery of Mega Spilaio in Greece and executes 22 monks and visitors as part of reprisals that culminated a few days later with the Massacre of Kalavryta.\nBULLET::::- 1953 – U.S. President Dwight D. Eisenhower delivers his \"Atoms for Peace\" speech, which leads to an American program to supply equipment and information on nuclear power to schools, hospitals, and research institutions around the world.\nBULLET::::- 1955 – The Flag of Europe is adopted by Council of Europe.\nBULLET::::- 1962 – Workers at four New York City newspapers (this later increases to nine) go on strike for 114 days.\nBULLET::::- 1963 – Pan Am Flight 214, a Boeing 707, is struck by lightning and crashes near Elkton, Maryland, killing all 81 people on board.\nBULLET::::- 1966 – The Greek ship sinks in a storm in the Aegean Sea, killing over 200.\nBULLET::::- 1969 – Olympic Airways Flight 954 strikes a mountain outside of Keratea, Greece, killing 90 people in the worst crash of a Douglas DC-6 in history.\nBULLET::::- 1971 – Indo-Pakistani War: The Indian Navy launches an attack on West Pakistan's port city of Karachi.\nBULLET::::- 1972 – United Airlines Flight 553, a Boeing 737, crashes after aborting its landing attempt at Chicago Midway International Airport, killing 45. This is the first-ever loss of a Boeing 737.\nBULLET::::- 1974 – A plebiscite results in the abolition of monarchy in Greece.\nBULLET::::- 1980 – Former Beatle John Lennon is murdered in front of The Dakota in New York City.\nBULLET::::- 1985 – The South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation, the regional intergovernmental organization and geopolitical union in South Asia is established.\nBULLET::::- 1987 – Cold War: The Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty is signed by U.S. President Ronald Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev in the White House.\nBULLET::::- 1987 – An Israeli army tank transporter kills four Palestinian refugees and injures seven others during a traffic accident at the Erez Crossing on the Israel–Gaza Strip border, which has been cited as one of the events which sparked the First Intifada.\nBULLET::::- 1988 – A United States Air Force A-10 Thunderbolt II crashes into an apartment complex in Remscheid, Germany, killing 5 people and injuring 50 others.\nBULLET::::- 1990 – Galileo (spacecraft) flies past Earth.\nBULLET::::- 1991 – The leaders of Russia, Belarus and Ukraine sign an agreement dissolving the Soviet Union and establishing the Commonwealth of Independent States.\nBULLET::::- 1992 – Galileo (spacecraft) flies past Earth.\nBULLET::::- 1998 – Eighty-one people are killed by armed groups in Algeria.\nBULLET::::- 2004 – The Cusco Declaration is signed in Cusco, Peru, establishing the South American Community of Nations.\nBULLET::::- 2009 – Bombings in Baghdad, Iraq, kill 127 people and injure 448 others.\nBULLET::::- 2010 – With the second launch of the Falcon 9 and the first launch of the Dragon, SpaceX becomes the first private company to successfully launch, orbit and recover a spacecraft.\n\nBULLET::::- 2010 – The Japanese solar-sail spacecraft IKAROS passes the planet Venus at a distance of about 80,800 km.\nBULLET::::- 2013 – Riots break out in Singapore after a fatal accident in Little India.\nBULLET::::- 2013 – Metallica performs a show in Antarctica, making them the first band to perform on all 7 continents.\n\nBULLET::::- 65 BC – Horace, Roman poet (d. 8 BC)\nBULLET::::- 1021 – Wang Anshi, Chinese economist and chancellor (d. 1086)\nBULLET::::- 1412 – Astorre II Manfredi, Italian lord (d. 1468)\nBULLET::::- 1418 – Queen Jeonghui, Queen consort of Korea (d. 1483)\nBULLET::::- 1424 – Anselm Adornes, Belgian merchant, politician and diplomat (d. 1483)\nBULLET::::- 1538 – Miklós Istvánffy, Hungarian politician (d. 1615)\nBULLET::::- 1542 – Mary, Queen of Scots (d. 1587)\nBULLET::::- 1558 – François de La Rochefoucauld, Catholic cardinal (d. 1645)\nBULLET::::- 1678 – Horatio Walpole, 1st Baron Walpole, English politician and diplomat, British Ambassador to France (d. 1757)\nBULLET::::- 1699 – Maria Josepha of Austria (d. 1757)\nBULLET::::- 1708 – Francis I, Holy Roman Emperor (d. 1765)\nBULLET::::- 1724 – Claude Balbastre, French organist and composer (d. 1799)\nBULLET::::- 1730 – Jan Ingenhousz, Dutch physician, physiologist, and botanist (d. 1799)\nBULLET::::- 1731 – František Xaver Dušek, Czech pianist and composer (d. 1799)\nBULLET::::- 1756 – Archduke Maximilian Francis of Austria (d. 1801)\nBULLET::::- 1765 – Eli Whitney, American engineer, invented the cotton gin (d. 1825)\nBULLET::::- 1795 – Peter Andreas Hansen, Danish astronomer and mathematician (d. 1874)\nBULLET::::- 1807 – Friedrich Traugott Kützing, German pharmacist, botanist and phycologist (d. 1893)\nBULLET::::- 1813 – August Belmont, Prussian-American financier and diplomat, 16th United States Ambassador to the Netherlands (d. 1890)\nBULLET::::- 1815 – Adolph Menzel, German painter and illustrator (d. 1905)\nBULLET::::- 1817 – Christian Emil Krag-Juel-Vind-Frijs, Danish lawyer and politician, 10th Prime Minister of Denmark (d. 1896)\nBULLET::::- 1818 – Charles III, Prince of Monaco (d. 1889)\nBULLET::::- 1822 – Jakov Ignjatović, Hungarian-Serbian author (d. 1889)\nBULLET::::- 1832 – Bjørnstjerne Bjørnson, Norwegian-French author and playwright, Nobel Prize laureate (d. 1910)\nBULLET::::- 1860 – Amanda McKittrick Ros, Irish author and poet (d. 1939)\nBULLET::::- 1861 – William C. Durant, American businessman, founded General Motors and Chevrolet (d. 1947)\nBULLET::::- 1861 – Aristide Maillol, French sculptor and painter (d. 1944)\nBULLET::::- 1861 – Georges Méliès, French actor, director, producer, and screenwriter (d. 1938)\nBULLET::::- 1862 – Georges Feydeau, French playwright (d. 1921)\nBULLET::::- 1863 – Charles Lincoln Edwards, American zoologist (d. 1937)\nBULLET::::- 1864 – Camille Claudel, French illustrator and sculptor (d. 1943)\nBULLET::::- 1865 – Rüdiger von der Goltz, German general (d. 1946)\nBULLET::::- 1865 – Jacques Hadamard, French mathematician and academic (d. 1963)\nBULLET::::- 1865 – Jean Sibelius, Finnish violinist and composer (d. 1957)\nBULLET::::- 1874 – Ernst Moro, Austrian physician and pediatrician (d. 1951)\nBULLET::::- 1875 – Frederik Buch, Danish actor and screenwriter (d. 1925)\nBULLET::::- 1877 – Paul Ladmirault, French pianist, violinist, and composer (d. 1944)\nBULLET::::- 1880 – Johannes Aavik, Estonian linguist and philologist (d. 1973)\nBULLET::::- 1881 – Albert Gleizes, French painter (d. 1953)\nBULLET::::- 1884 – Francis Balfour, English colonel and politician (d. 1965)\nBULLET::::- 1886 – Diego Rivera, Mexican painter and educator (d. 1957)\nBULLET::::- 1890 – Bohuslav Martinů, Czech-American pianist and composer (d. 1959)\nBULLET::::- 1892 – Marcus Lee Hansen, American historian, author, and academic (d. 1938)\nBULLET::::- 1894 – E. C. Segar, American cartoonist, created \"Popeye\" (d. 1938)\nBULLET::::- 1894 – James Thurber, American humorist and cartoonist (d. 1961)\nBULLET::::- 1899 – Arthur Leslie, English-Welsh actor and playwright (d. 1970)\nBULLET::::- 1899 – John Qualen, Canadian-American actor (d. 1987)\nBULLET::::- 1900 – Sun Li-jen, Chinese general and politician (d. 1990)\nBULLET::::- 1900 – Ants Oras, Estonian-American author and academic (d. 1982)\nBULLET::::- 1902 – Wifredo Lam, Cuban-French painter (d. 1982)\nBULLET::::- 1903 – Zelma Watson George, Black American opera singer (d. 1994)\nBULLET::::- 1908 – Concha Piquer, Spanish singer and actress (d. 1990)\nBULLET::::- 1908 – John A. Volpe, American soldier and politician, 61st Governor of Massachusetts (d. 1994)\nBULLET::::- 1911 – Lee J. Cobb, American actor (d. 1976)\nBULLET::::- 1911 – Nikos Gatsos, Greek poet and songwriter (d. 1992)\nBULLET::::- 1913 – Delmore Schwartz, American poet and short story writer (d. 1966)\nBULLET::::- 1914 – Floyd Tillman, American country music singer-songwriter and guitarist (d. 2003)\nBULLET::::- 1914 – Ernie Toshack, Australian cricketer (d. 2003)\nBULLET::::- 1915 – Ernest Lehman, American director, producer, and screenwriter (d. 2005)\nBULLET::::- 1916 – Richard Fleischer, American director, producer, and screenwriter (d. 2006)\nBULLET::::- 1917 – Ian Johnson, Australian cricketer and administrator (d. 1998)\nBULLET::::- 1919 – Peter Tali Coleman, Samoan-American lawyer and politician, 43rd Governor of American Samoa (d. 1997)\nBULLET::::- 1919 – Julia Robinson, American mathematician and theorist (d. 1985)\nBULLET::::- 1919 – Kateryna Yushchenko, Ukrainian computer scientist and academic (d. 2001)\nBULLET::::- 1920 – McDonald Bailey, Trinidadian-English sprinter and rugby player (d. 2013)\nBULLET::::- 1922 – Lucian Freud, German-English painter and illustrator (d. 2011)\nBULLET::::- 1922 – Jean Ritchie, American singer-songwriter (d. 2015)\nBULLET::::- 1923 – Dewey Martin, American actor (d. 2018)\nBULLET::::- 1923 – Rudolph Pariser, Chinese-American soldier and chemist\nBULLET::::- 1924 – Lionel Gilbert, Australian historian, author, and academic (d. 2015)\nBULLET::::- 1925 – Sammy Davis, Jr., American actor, singer, and dancer (d. 1990)\nBULLET::::- 1925 – Nasir Kazmi, Pakistani Urdu poet (d. 1972)\nBULLET::::- 1925 – Carmen Martín Gaite, Spanish author and poet (d. 2000)\nBULLET